list.name: Hydrogen-F
list.about: Hydrogen-F is a character mentioned in the Rick and Morty episode 'The Ricks Must Be Crazy.' He is a sentient being residing inside Rick's Microverse Battery. Although Hydrogen-F doesn't have a physical presence in the episode, his mention adds to the complexity and vastness of the Rick and Morty universe, which is filled with countless bizarre and unique entities.

list.name: Ice-T
list.about: Ice-T is a recurring character in the Rick and Morty series, known for his portrayal as a sentient, talking watermelon. In the episode 'Auto Erotic Assimilation,' Ice-T reveals himself to be an alien life form that joined a band with Rick in another dimension. This unexpected twist, featuring a popular real-life rapper as a fruit-based extraterrestrial, is a prime example of the show's surreal and unconventional humor.

list.name: Ideal Jerry
list.about: Ideal Jerry is an alternate version of Jerry Smith introduced in the episode 'The ABC's of Beth.' He represents the idealized version of Jerry as imagined by Beth. Ideal Jerry is depicted as a muscular, confident, and successful version of Jerry, serving as a satirical commentary on societal expectations and personal insecurities. His existence prompts Beth to question her own desires and motivations.

list.name: Insurance Rick
list.about: Insurance Rick is a character who appears in the episode 'The Rickshank Rickdemption' in Rick and Morty. He is a version of Rick who works in the insurance industry, handling claims for other Ricks. Insurance Rick showcases the show's ability to explore various alternate versions of its central characters, each with their own unique traits and occupations.

list.name: Investigator Rick
list.about: Investigator Rick is a character mentioned in the Rick and Morty episode 'Close Rick-counters of the Rick Kind.' He is part of the Council of Ricks and is known for his investigative skills. While Investigator Rick does not appear in the episode, his mention hints at the diverse roles and professions that exist within the Council of Ricks, further expanding the show's multiverse.

list.name: Invisi-trooper
list.about: The Invisi-trooper is a character briefly shown in the Rick and Morty episode 'Ricksy Business.' This character is a member of the alien race known as the Gromflomites and possesses the ability to turn invisible. The inclusion of the Invisi-trooper highlights the show's attention to detail in creating a rich and diverse intergalactic world.

list.name: Izzy
list.about: Izzy is a character who appears in the Rick and Morty episode 'Anatomy Park.' She is the daughter of Dr. Xenon Bloom, the creator of Anatomy Park. Izzy plays a crucial role in the episode as she becomes trapped inside the body of a homeless man who is part of the theme park. Her presence adds an emotional element to the episode, as the characters race against time to rescue her.

list.name: Jackie
list.about: Jackie is a character mentioned in the Rick and Morty episode 'Mortynight Run.' She is an ex-girlfriend of Morty who is mentioned during a conversation between Morty and Fart, an alien with telepathic powers. While Jackie herself does not appear in the episode, her mention offers a glimpse into Morty's personal life and relationships outside of his adventures with Rick.

list.name: Jacob
list.about: Jacob is a character who appears in the Rick and Morty episode 'Big Trouble in Little Sanchez.' He is a student at Harry Herpson High School and is shown as a close friend of Morty. Jacob's character adds depth to Morty's social circle and provides opportunities for character development and interactions beyond the central duo of Rick and Morty.

list.name: Jacqueline
list.about: Jacqueline is a character mentioned in the Rick and Morty episode 'Rickmancing the Stone.' She is a woman who is briefly mentioned during a conversation between Rick and Hemorrhage. While Jacqueline does not appear in the episode, her mention adds to the world-building and expands the scope of the post-apocalyptic wasteland where the episode takes place.

list.name: Jaguar
list.about: Jaguar is a character introduced in the Rick and Morty episode 'Pickle Rick.' He is a mysterious and skilled mercenary who assists Rick in his escape from a high-security facility. Jaguar's character is voiced by actor Danny Trejo, adding an extra layer of badassery to his portrayal. The inclusion of Jaguar demonstrates the show's ability to incorporate guest characters that align with its over-the-top and action-packed tone.

list.name: Jamey
list.about: Jamey is a character who appears in the Rick and Morty episode 'Look Who's Purging Now.' He is a young boy who becomes Morty's companion during their visit to a planet where an annual purge takes place. Jamey's presence serves as a vehicle for exploring the moral dilemmas and consequences of societal norms in the Rick and Morty universe.

list.name: Jan-Michael Vincent
list.about: Jan-Michael Vincent is a character mentioned in the Rick and Morty episode 'Interdimensional Cable 2: Tempting Fate.' He is a fictional actor known for his roles in 'Airwolf' and 'Jan-Michael Vincent's Daycare.' The show often references real-life pop culture and media, and the inclusion of Jan-Michael Vincent is a playful nod to the actor's fame and the absurdity of his fictitious daycare show.

list.name: Jerry 5-126
list.about: Jerry 5-126 is a version of Jerry Smith introduced in the Rick and Morty episode 'The ABC's of Beth.' In an alternate reality, Beth creates a clone of Jerry to take care of the family while she goes on adventures. Jerry 5-126 represents a more competent and successful version of Jerry, highlighting the show's exploration of different iterations of its characters and the potential outcomes of their lives.

list.name: Jerry Smith
list.about: Jerry Smith is a central character in the Rick and Morty series. He is the husband of Beth Smith and the father of Summer and Morty. Jerry is often portrayed as an insecure and bumbling character, providing comedic relief and serving as a contrast to the brilliance and confidence of Rick. His character explores themes of insecurity, self-worth, and the complexities of family dynamics.

list.name: Celebrity Jerry
list.about: Celebrity Jerry is a character introduced in the Rick and Morty episode 'Big Trouble in Little Sanchez.' He is a version of Jerry who becomes a famous celebrity in an alternate reality. Celebrity Jerry's character is a satirical commentary on the fleeting nature of fame and the impact it has on a person's identity and relationships.

list.name: Jerry's Mytholog
list.about: Jerry's Mytholog is a character who appears in the Rick and Morty episode 'Big Trouble in Little Sanchez.' He represents Jerry's insecurities and self-doubt personified, manifesting as a mythological creature. Jerry's Mytholog serves as a visual representation of the internal struggles and emotional challenges faced by Jerry, highlighting the show's ability to explore psychological concepts through imaginative storytelling.

list.name: Jessica
list.about: Jessica is a character in the Rick and Morty series and a classmate of Morty at Harry Herpson High School. Morty has a crush on Jessica, and their interactions often involve Morty's awkward attempts to impress her. Jessica's character serves as a recurring element in Morty's personal life, exploring themes of teenage romance and the complexities of navigating relationships.
